    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-length-of-an-arc">
    <title>Length of an arc</title>
    <p>
        An arc of a circle is a portion of the circumference (the curved edge) of the circle.
    </p>
    <p>
        There are two main types of arcs:
    </p>
    <p>
        <ol>
        <li>
            <p>
            Minor Arc – less than half the circle (less than <m>180^\circ</m>).
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
            Major Arc – more than half the circle (more than <m>180^\circ</m>).
            </p>
        </li>
        </ol>
    </p>
    <p>
        The length of an arc depends on the central angle (the angle subtended at the center 
        of the circle) and the radius of the circle.
    </p>
    <p>
        See the figure below showing the circle divided in diffrent sections.
    </p>
    <image width="50%">
    <latex-image label="sec">
        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=5, every node/.style={font=\huge}]
        % Circle
        \draw[very thick,dashed] (0,0) circle (1.1);
        \draw[very thick, blue] (0,0) circle (1);
        
        % Define points
        \coordinate (O) at (0,0);
        \coordinate (A) at (1,0);  % Point on x-axis
        \coordinate (B) at ({cos(60)},{sin(60)}); % 60 degree point on circle
        
        % Radii
        \draw[very thick, red,&lt;-&gt;,below] (O) -- (A);
        \draw[very thick, red] (O) -- (B);
        \node[black!60!black, below] at (0.5,0) {Radius};
        
        
        % Arc
        \draw[thick, red, -&gt;] (A) arc[start angle=0,end angle=60,radius=1cm];
        \node[red] at (1.3,0.55) {Minor Arc};
        \node[blue] at (0,1.04) {Major Arc};
        
        % Sector
        \fill[red!20, opacity=0.5] (O) -- (A) arc[start angle=0,end angle=60,radius=1cm] -- cycle;
        \node[red!80!black] at (0.5,0.15) {Sector};
        
        % Theta angle
        \draw[-&gt;] (0.2,0) arc[start angle=0,end angle=60,radius=0.2];
        \node at (0.25,0.1) {$\theta$};
        
        % Chord
        \draw[thick, black!60!black] (-1,0.2) -- (0.2,-1);
        \draw[very thick,&lt;-&lt;, green!60!black, dashed] (-1,0.3) -- (0.3,-1);
        \node[green!60!black] at (-0.2,-0.3) {Chord};
        
        % Segment
        \fill[red!30, opacity=0.4] (A) arc[start angle=0,end angle=60,radius=1cm] -- (B) -- cycle;
        \node[red!60!black,rotate=135] at (-0.7,-0.4) {Segment};
        
        % Circumference arrow
        \draw[-&gt;, blue, thick] (-0.87,-0.5) arc[start angle=210, end angle=240, radius=1.1];
        \node[rotate=135] at (-1,-0.7) {Circumference};
        \end{tikzpicture}
    </latex-image>
        
    </image>
    <p>
        The length of an arrc of a circle is <m>\frac{\theta}{360}</m> of the 
        circumference of the circle
    </p>
    <p>
        In general. The length <m>l</m> of an arc of a circle which substends 
        an angle <m>\theta</m> at the centre of the circle is given by 
        <m>l=\frac{\theta}{360} \times 2 \pi </m>
    </p>

    
    <activity>
        <p>
            <m>\text{Work in groups}</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
