                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
        

        <p>A semi-circle is a sector of a circle. Where the term sector is derived from the word section.</p>
        <p>Arc length of a semi-circle is given by  <m> \frac {180^ \circ} {360^ \circ} \times \pi \text { d or}  
         \frac {180^ \circ} {360^ \circ} \times 2 \pi r = \frac {1}{2} \pi \text{ d or } \frac {1}{2}(2 \pi r)</m></p>
        
        <p> Do an extended activity to explore on how to calculate the length of the arc of a
             quarter circle by simply cutting the 
            semi-circle and repeat the steps of measuring circumference length </p>
        <p> A quarter a circle is called a quadrant. So how many Quadrants do we have? <m>\textbf{ 4 }.</m> </p>
        <p>A quarter-circle is also a sector of a circle.</p>
        
        <p>Arc length of a quarter-circle is <m>\frac {90^ \circ} {360^ \circ} \times 
        \pi \text{ d or } \frac {90^ \circ} {360^ \circ} \times 2 \pi r =  \frac {1}{4} \pi \text{ d  or } \frac {1}{4}(2 \pi r)</m></p>
        
        <p>
            Can you compute one for a three quarter-circle?
        </p>

        

    </activity>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                An arc of a circle substends an angle <m>60^\circ</m> at the centre 
                of the circle. Find the length of the arc if the circle is <m>42\, \text{cm}</m>. (Take <m>\pi = \frac{22}{7}</m>)
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                The length <m>l</m> of the arc is given by;
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>l=\frac{\theta}{360} \times 2 \pi r</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>\theta=60^\circ</m>, r <m>=42</m> cm
            </p>
            <p>
                Therefore.
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>l= \amp \frac{60}{360} \times 2 \times \frac{22}{7} 42</mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp 44 \, \text{cm} </mrow>
                    
                </md>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Find the arc length of the figure below. Use <m>\pi=3.142</m>
            </p>
            <image width="50%">
            <latex-image label="sect2">
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                    \coordinate (O) at (0,0);
                    \coordinate (A) at (1,0); % 0 degrees
